        "created_at": "2021-08-06T20:18:09.000Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group quote-modified\" data-post=\"1\" data-topic=\"172574\">\n<blockquote>\n<p>I posed this question via Instgram and Facebook yesterday - my newest shipment of Hebrart BdB, disgorged on May 6, 2020, is labelled as Brut, as it has been in the past.  I was checking out William Kelly\u2019s review and saw that he listed an Extra Brut bottling, disgorged on the same date.  His review also seemed to imply, if I read it correctly, that what used to be bottled as Brut was now being bottled as Extra Brut, to the benefit of the wine as the lower dosage revealed more of the fruit quality.  So I wondered if Hebrart was now doing both a Brut and Extra Brut, and disgorging them at the same time, or if the US label just continued to read Brut, which would encompass Extra Brut anyway?  Further confusing the issue, I saw a picture of the label on CT listing Extra Brut.</p>\n<p>Responses on Facebook, referencing the Skurnik website, indicate that they do both.  William Kelly was kind enough to chime in and say he might have \u201cgot the wrong end of the stick\u201d and would also be interested to get some details from Skurnik, but reiterated that the dosage has been trending lower chez Hebrart in any case.</p>\n<p>A search of CT shows very little in the way of an Extra Brut version (4 bottles in cellars and no notes, which usually means a wine added by mistake, but could just be a new version) and Wine Searcher Pro doesn\u2019t have much to offer either.</p>\n<p>Anyone have more information?  I don\u2019t immediately see a website for Hebrart.  If he\u2019s doing both, and disgorging them side by side, I\u2019d love to do a comparison tasting sometime.</p>\n<p>Thanks!</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.instagram.com/p/CSNNaJoLGQG/\" class=\"inline-onebox\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\">Sarah Kirschbaum on Instagram: \"Curious about the labeling here. This bottle clearly states Brut on both the front and back, but the May 2020 disgorgement was bottled as Extra Brut according to the review from @wgfkelley (possibly others). I have seen pictures of the same label with \"Extra Brut\" listed. It strikes me as unlikely, though not impossible, that they did two versions. Or could this be a matter of not wanting to change the label and thus have to do a new registration in the US market? Anyone know?\"</a></p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>All I know is that I had the bottle pictured recently and it was boss. Love the producer, pretty much across the range</p>",
