      {
        "id": 3211323,
        "name": "Otto Forsberg",
        "username": "Otto_Forsberg",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/otto_forsberg/{size}/2907_2.png",
        "created_at": "2021-08-06T21:47:16.000Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-post=\"5\" data-topic=\"172574\">\n<blockquote>\n<p>\"f I read it correctly, that what used to be bottled as Brut was now being bottled as Extra Brut, to the benefit of the wine as the lower dosage revealed more of the fruit quality. \"</p>\n<p>Is this correct?  My understanding is that Extra Brut actually has a higher dosage of sugar than Brut \u2013 no?</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>Do you mean that normally Extra Brut would have higher dosage than Brut?</p>\n<p>That is incorrect.</p>\n<p>Brut Nature: 0-2 g/l<br>\nExtra Brut: 0-6 g/l<br>\nBrut 0-12 g/l</p>\n<p>(And they do have leeway of 3 g/l so values up to 5 g/l, 9 g/l and 15 g/l are permitted.)</p>",
